<section id="resources.information.concepts.design.patterns.introduction.patternRepositories"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" 
         xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation="http://www.solms.co.za/schemas/doc/solmsDoc/solmsDoc.xsd" 
         xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

  <title>Pattern repositories</title>
  <para>
     There are many design patterns repositories on the web. Two of the most widely used
     generic patterns repositories are
     <itemizedlist>
       <listitem><para>
         <ulink url="http://hillside.net"><literal><![CDATA[http://hillside.net]]></literal></ulink> and
       </para></listitem>
       <listitem><para>
         the Portland pattern repository, <ulink url="http://c2.com/cgi/wiki"><literal><![CDATA[http://c2.com/cgi/wiki]]></literal></ulink>  .
       </para></listitem>
     </itemizedlist>
     Other pattern repositories which you may find useful include
     <itemizedlist>
       <listitem><para>
         the <emphasis>Object-Oriented Pattern Digest</emphasis>  at
         <ulink url="http://patternDigest.com"><literal><![CDATA[http://patternDigest.com]]></literal></ulink>
       </para></listitem>
       <listitem><para>
         as well as the pattern repository hosted by <emphasis>TheServerSide</emphasis> at
         <ulink url="http://www.theserverside.com/patterns"><literal><![CDATA[http://www.theserverside.com/patterns]]></literal></ulink>.
       </para></listitem>
     </itemizedlist>
  </para>
  <para>
    Having identified a new pattern,you may want to submit the pattern to one or more of these repositories.
    Additionally you may want to consider hosting a design pattern repository within your own organization,
    collecting patterns particularly useful in your domain.
  </para>
</section>
